rocesses of mapping territories of self-knowing and self-expression, both cognitively in the imagination and on paper during the mapping exercise, exploring how meaning is given to space, and how it is transformed. Using the women’s "es and maps, the book focuses on the false binary of public-private, the practices of home and family, and religious nationalism and spiritual self-seeking, to demonstrate the women’s challenges to the structural, symbolic, and interpersonal violence of colonial discourses and practices related to gender, knowledge, and power in Trinidadian society.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 0aGayszCaribbean AreaxSocial conditions. 0aLesbiansxIdentity. 0aLesbianszCaribbean AreaxSocial conditions. 0aWomenxIdentity. 0aWomenxSexual behaviorzCaribbean Area. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aCaribbean studies, women's studies, LGBTQ, Sociology, gender, Trinidad, sexual identity, self-expression, spirituality, religion, sexuality, queer, nationalism, social class, interpersonal violence, decolonization.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076647940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781978821408423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781978821408/original  a978-3-11-076647-9  Rutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK